dea, but I’m wondering if I should apply them to local variables. It's not strictly necessary, though it might make things clearer. Maybe I should also consider adding type imports—though I'm not sure if they're needed for all variables. I'll weigh these options moving forward!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"Updated the failing test to avoid Java `HttpClient` server-push behavior, which did not deliver push promises in this environment.\\n\\nChanges made in:\\n\\n- `tests/src/io.ktor/ktor-server-netty-jvm/3.2.0/src/test/kotlin/io_ktor/ktor_server_netty_jvm/NettyHttp2HandlerTest.kt`\\n\\nWhat changed:\\n- Replaced the Java `HttpClient` HTTP/2 client with a Netty HTTP/2 client.\\n- The Netty client explicitly sends HTTP/2 settings with server push enabled:\\n  - `Http2Settings().pushEnabled(true)`\\n- The client now:\\n  - Negotiates HTTP/2 over TLS with ALPN.\\n  - Sends the root request over an HTTP/2 stream.\\n  - Accepts inbound pushed streams through `Http2MultiplexHandler`.\\n  - Verifies both the root response and pushed response bodies.\\n\\nThis should allow Ktor’s `call.push(\\\"/pushed\\\")` path to proceed past `connection.remote().allowPushTo()` and exercise the reflective `NettyHttp2Handler` push-stream setup call sites.\", \"textSignature\": \"{\\\"v\\\":1,\\\"id\\\":\\\"msg_0a6704ccfacdad40016a28b98720188197b822584e7581777f\\\",\\\"phase\\\":\\\"final_answer\\\"}\"}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 4788, \"output\": 915, \"cacheRead\": 47104, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 52807, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1781053807859, \"responseId\": \"resp_0a6704ccfacdad40016a28b97099e081979f200499812210a2\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/io.ktor:ktor-server-netty-jvm:3.2.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-10T01-08-12-245636Z.log:5609:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\"